# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcohol-by-volume
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The word *aquavit* derives from the Latin *aqua vitae*, "water of life." Compare the words *whisky* and *whiskey*, from Gaelic *uisce beatha*, which has the same meaning.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Likewise, clear fruit brandy is called *eau de vie* (French for "water of life").
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Akvavit is an important part of Nordic drinking culture, where it is often drunk during festive gatherings, such as Christmas dinners and the Midsummer celebration, and as an aperitif.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Iceland, Sweden, Denmark, and Germany, aquavit is chilled and often drunk in a single gulp from a small shot glass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] This is usually attributed to tradition.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Norway, it is not generally chilled, but enjoyed slowly.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Sweden, aquavit is commonly consumed immediately following a song, called a snapsvisa.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The most well-known song is "Helan Går".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Finland and Sweden, aquavit consumed from a shot glass is also commonly associated with crayfish parties, which are traditionally held during late August.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Denmark, aquavit is called snaps or akvavit, and is primarily consumed in December during Christmas lunches or around Easter during Easter lunches.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] It is consumed year-round, though, mainly for lunches of traditional Danish dishes where beer is also always on the table.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Norway, where most aquavit is matured in oak casks, the drink is served at room temperature in tulip-shaped glasses.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Aquavit arguably complements beer well, and its consumption is very often preceded by a swig of beer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Akvavit must be distilled from an agricultural base, most commonly grain or potatoes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Similarly to gin, it is flavoured with botanicals.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The dominant flavours must be caraway or dill, or sometimes both.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Swedish Akvavit must also contain fennel in order to be labelled as such.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Other common botanicals include cardamom, cumin, anise, and coriander.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The Danish distillery Aalborg makes an akvavit distilled with amber, which imparts a pine-like citrusy note.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The Aalborg brand is now produced in Norway by Arcus Group.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The recipes and flavours differ between brands, with each brand's unique characteristics coming from distillation methods and supporting botanicals in their blends.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Un-aged Akvavit is clear, while aged Akvavit typically has a pale straw-to-golden hue, depending on how long it has been aged in oak casks (most common in Norway) or the amount of colourant used.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Normally, a darker colour suggests a higher age or the use of young casks, although artificial caramel colouring and infusing fruits or botanicals for colour and flavour are permitted before bottling.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Clear akvavit is often called *taffel*, meaning table aquavit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Taffel aquavit is typically aged in old casks that do not colour the finished spirit, or it is not aged at all.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The earliest known reference to "aquavit" is found in a 1531 letter from the Lord of Bergenshus castle, (Norway) Eske Bille, to Olav Engelbrektsson, the last Roman Catholic Archbishop of Norway.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The letter, dated April 13 and accompanying a package, offers the archbishop "some water which is called Aqua Vite and is a help for all sort of illness which a man can have both internally and externally".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] While this claim for the medicinal properties of the drink may be rather inflated, aquavit is popularly believed to ease the digestion of rich foods.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Norway, it is drunk at celebrations, particularly Christmas, Easter, or May 17 (Norwegian Constitution Day).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Denmark, it is traditionally associated with Christmas and Easter lunches.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In Sweden, it is a staple of the traditional midsummer celebrations dinner, usually drunk while singing one of many drinking songs.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] It is usually drunk as snaps during meals, especially during the appetizer course — along with pickled herring, crayfish, lutefisk, or smoked fish.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] In this regard, it is popularly quipped that aquavit helps the fish swim down to the stomach.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] It is also a regular in traditional Norwegian Christmas meals, including roasted rib of pork and rib of lamb (*pinnekjøtt*).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The spices and the alcohol are said to help digest the meal, which is very rich in fat.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Among the most important brands are Løiten, Lysholm, Opland, and Simers from Norway; Aalborg and Brøndum from Denmark; and O.P.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] While the Danish and Swedish variants are normally very light in colour, most of the Norwegian brands are matured in oak casks for at least six months, and for some brands even as long as 12 years, making them generally darker in colour.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] While members of all three nations can be found to claim that "their" style of aquavit is the best as a matter of national pride, Swedish *akvavit* is typically the most renowned around the world, specifically so in the culinary scene.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Whilst the Norwegian *akevitt* tends to have if not the most distinctive character, then at least the most overpowering flavour and deepest colour due to the aging process.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Peculiar to the Norwegian tradition are *Linje Aquavits* (such as "Løiten Linie" and "Lysholm Linie").
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Linje Aquavit is named after the tradition of sending oak barrels of aquavit with ships from Norway to Australia and back again, thereby passing the equator ("linje") twice before being bottled.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The constant movement, high humidity, and fluctuating temperature cause the spirit to extract more flavour and contribute to accelerated maturation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Norwegian aquavit distillers Anora (formerly Arcus) carried out a test where they tried to emulate the rocking of the casks aboard the "Linje" ships while the oak barrels were subjected to the weather elements, as they would aboard a ship.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The finished product was, according to Anora, far from the taste that a proper *linje* aquavit should have.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Therefore, to this day, boats loaded with "Linie Aquavit" set sail from Norway to Australia and back again before they are bottled and sold as part of the Norwegian Christmas traditions, but also enjoyed all year round.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Aquavit was seldom produced outside of the Nordic countries, but that began to change dramatically starting around 2010, especially in the United States, and particularly in areas that have larger concentrations of people with a Nordic heritage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] An exception, however, is Northern Germany, and in particular the German state of Schleswig-Holstein, which was part of Denmark until the 19th century (see History of Schleswig-Holstein) and still has a notable Danish minority.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Among the most important German brands are Bommerlunder from Flensburg, Kieler Sprotte from Kiel, and Malteserkreuz.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Malteserkreuz has been produced in Berlin since 1924 by a subsidiary of Sweden's Vin & Sprit AB (now Pernod Ricard), the producer of many Swedish akvavits, and can be considered a German imitation of the Nordic aquavits since it is based on an original Danish recipe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Brands from Schleswig-Holstein, however, often have a long history, comparable to their Nordic counterparts.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Bommerlunder, for instance, has been made since 1760.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Aquavit is also an important part of the traditional cuisine of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] German aquavit is virtually always distilled from fermented grain and generally has an alcohol content of 38% by volume, marginally less than Scandinavian aquavits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Many distilleries in the United States produce aquavit, especially in parts of the country with high populations of people of Nordic heritage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Examples include Colorado, Minnesota, Michigan, Wisconsin, Montana, Illinois, Oregon, New Hampshire, and Washington.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] The Midwest states in particular do quite well for the category and have produced numerous internationally acclaimed/award-winning brands.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] See List of Akvavit Producers in the United States for brand names and distilleries.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Aquavit is also seeing a rise in popularity in Canada, particularly in Scandinavian settlements.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/akvavit] Notable brands include Spirit of York Co in Toronto, Ontario, Drum Distilling Co in Drumheller, Alberta, and The Newfoundland Distillery Co, in Clarkes Beach Newfoundland.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] France, alcohol by volume is often referred to as **degrees Gay-Lussac** (after the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac), although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac convention uses the International Standard Atmosphere value for temperature, 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a change in volume.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass causes a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solutions above 24% causes a decrease in volume.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar solutions is called "partial molar volume".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Water and ethanol are both polar solvents.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] When water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field of the other.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is usually found in non-polar mixtures.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Thus, alc/vol is not the same as volume fraction expressed as a percentage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (commonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured separately.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] For example, to make 100 mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solution, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Whereas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50 mL of ethanol and 50 mL of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure less than 100 mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will contain a higher concentration of ethanol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The difference is not large, with the maximum difference being less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certified as a certain alcohol brand or label.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] For example, in the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada and European Union whisky is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Low-alcohol beers (<0.5) are considered in some countries such as Iran as permitted (halal) despite alcohol being banned.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typically the lowest commercially sold 0.05.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinking low-alcohol drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The low concentration severely limits the rate of intake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Quickly drinking 1.5 L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% BAC in a study of German volunteers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Healthy human kidneys can only excrete 0.8–1.0 L of water per hour, making water intoxication likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The process of ethanol fermentation will slow down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too concentrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for non-distilled alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is at 8–12%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14–18%, with speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Any higher would require distillation, producing liquor.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Details about typical amounts of alcohol contained in various beverages can be found in the articles about them.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] During the production of wine and beer, yeast is added to a sugary solution.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] During fermentation, the yeasts consume the sugars and produce alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The density of sugar in water is greater than the density of alcohol in water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] A hydrometer is used to measure the change in specific gravity (SG) of the solution before and after fermentation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The volume of alcohol in the solution can then be estimated.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] There are a number of empirical formulae which brewers and winemakers use to estimate the alcohol content of the liquor made.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Specific gravity is the density of a liquid relative to that of water, i.e., if the density of the liquid is 1.05 times that of water, it has a specific gravity of 1.05.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] In UK brewing usage, it is customary to regard the reference value for water to be 1000, so the specific gravity of the same example beer would be quoted as 1050.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The formulas here assume that the former definition is used for specific gravity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] During ethanol fermentation the yeast converts one mole of sugar into two moles of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] where 46.069 is the molar mass of ethanol and 180.156 is the molar mass of glucose and fructose.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] SG can be measured using an hydrometer and Brix can be calculated from SG.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] SG drop is how much the SG decreased during fermentation (at 20 degree C).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The factor 135 is most accurate in the center of the SG drop range of 0.000 to 0.179.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Advanced formula derived from Carl Balling empirical formulas.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The formula compensates for changes in SG with changes in alcohol concentration and for the fact that not all sugar is converted into alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] where SG final is the specific gravity when fermentation ends, Plato start is the sugar by weight when fermentation begins, Plato final is the sugar by weight when fermentation ends.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Brix can be used instead of Plato as they are nearly identical.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol *proof*, which in the United States is twice the alcohol-by-volume (alc/vol) number.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] This may lead to confusion over similar products bought in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] For example, Stroh rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as *Stroh 80* when sold in Europe, but is named *Stroh 160* when sold in the United States.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] In the United Kingdom, proof is 1.75 times the number (expressed as a percentage).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] For example, 40% alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] However, since 1980, alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcohol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] In the United States, Arkansas, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to **alcohol by weight** (**ABW**), expressed as a percentage of total mass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than the ABW.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alcohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcohol, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with the density of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-by-volume] However, because of the miscibility of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather depends upon the concentration of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Short-term adverse effects include generalized impairment of neurocognitive function, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, and symptoms of hangover.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is addictive and can result in alcohol use disorder, dependence, and withdrawal upon cessation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The adverse effects of alcohol on health are most significant when it is used in excessive quantities or with heavy frequency.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, in 2023, the World Health Organization published a statement in The Lancet Public Health that concluded, "no safe amount of alcohol consumption for cancers and health can be established".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In high amounts, alcohol may cause loss of consciousness or, in severe cases, death.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Many governmental agencies and organizations issue alcohol consumption recommendations.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has been produced and consumed by humans for its psychoactive effects since at least 13,000 years ago, when the earliest known beer was brewed by the Natufian culture in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is the second most consumed psychoactive drug globally, behind caffeine, with global sales of alcoholic beverages exceeding US$1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol is generally socially acceptable and is legal in most countries, unlike with many other recreational substances.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, there are often restrictions on alcohol sale and use, for instance a minimum age for drinking and laws against public drinking and drinking and driving.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has considerable societal and cultural significance and has important social roles in much of the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drinking establishments, such as bars and nightclubs, revolve primarily around the sale and consumption of alcoholic beverages, and parties, festivals, and social gatherings commonly involve alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is related to various societal problems, including drunk driving, accidental injuries, sexual assaults, domestic abuse, and violent crime.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol remains illegal for sale and consumption in a number of countries, mainly in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] While some religions, including Islam, prohibit alcohol consumption, other religions, such as Christianity and Shinto, utilize alcohol in sacrament and libation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is commonly consumed as the recreational active substance of alcoholic beverages such as beer, wine, and spirits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Consumption in social settings may enhance sociability.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] While research on the societal benefits of alcohol is rare, in a study from the UK, regular but moderate drinking was correlated with happiness, feeling that life was worthwhile, and satisfaction with life.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Community pubs had less variation in visible group sizes and longer, more focused conversations than those in city centre bars.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drinking regularly at a community pub led to higher trust in others and better networking with the local community, compared to non-drinkers and city centre bar drinkers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, according to a causal path analysis, alcohol consumption was not the cause, but rather satisfaction with life resulted in greater happiness and an inclination to visit pubs and develop a regular drinking venue.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) uses a figure of 6.93 kilocalories (29.0 kJ) per gram of alcohol (5.47 kcal or 22.9 kJ per mL) for calculating food energy.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] For distilled spirits, a standard serving in the United States is 44 mL (1.5 US fl oz), which at 40% ethanol (80 proof), would be 14 grams and 98 calories.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic drinks are considered empty calorie foods because other than food energy they contribute no essential nutrients.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, alcohol is a significant source of food energy for individuals with alcoholism and those who engage in binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] For example, individuals with drunkorexia engage in the combination of self-imposed malnutrition and binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In alcoholics who get most of their daily calories from alcohol, a deficiency of thiamine (vitamin B1) can produce Korsakoff syndrome, which is associated with serious brain damage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] When fomepizole is not available, ethanol can be used to treat or prevent methanol or ethylene glycol poisoning.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The rate-limiting steps for the elimination of ethanol are in common with these substances, so it competes with other alcohols for the alcohol dehydrogenase enzyme.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Methanol itself is not highly toxic, but its metabolites formaldehyde and formic acid are; therefore, to reduce the rate of production and concentration of these harmful metabolites, ethanol can be ingested or injected.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] This avoids the production of toxic aldehyde and carboxylic acid derivatives, and reduces the more serious toxic effects of the glycols when crystallized in the kidneys.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethylene glycol poisoning can be treated in the same way.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a long association of military use, and has been called "liquid courage" for its role in preparing troops for battle, anesthetize injured soldiers, and celebrate military victories.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It has also served as a coping mechanism for combat stress reactions and a means of decompression from combat to everyday life.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can have analgesic (pain-relieving) effects, which is why some people with chronic pain turn to alcohol to self-medicate and try to alleviate their physical discomfort.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] People with social anxiety disorder commonly self-medicate with alcohol to overcome their highly set inhibitions.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, self-medicating excessively for prolonged periods of time with alcohol often makes the symptoms of anxiety or depression worse.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] This is believed to occur as a result of the changes in brain chemistry from long-term use.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A 2023 systematic review highlights the non-addictive use of alcohol for managing developmental issues, personality traits, and psychiatric symptoms, emphasizing the need for informed, harm-controlled approaches to alcohol consumption within a personalized health policy framework.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is classified as a teratogen—a substance known to cause birth defects; according to the U.S.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), alcohol consumption by women who are not using birth control increases the risk of fetal alcohol spectrum disorders (FASDs).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] This group of conditions encompasses fetal alcohol syndrome, partial fetal alcohol syndrome, alcohol-related neurodevelopmental disorder, static encephalopathy, and alcohol-related birth defects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The CDC currently recommends complete abstinence from alcoholic beverages for women of child-bearing age who are pregnant or trying to become pregnant.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In patients who have a peptic ulcer disease (PUD), the mucosal layer is broken down by ethanol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] PUD is commonly associated with the bacteria *Helicobacter pylori*, which secretes a toxin that weakens the mucosal wall, allowing acid and protein enzymes to penetrate the weakened barrier.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Because alcohol stimulates the stomach to secrete acid, a person with PUD should avoid drinking alcohol on an empty stomach.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drinking alcohol causes more acid release, which further damages the already-weakened stomach wall.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Complications of this disease could include a burning pain in the abdomen, bloating, and, in severe cases, the presence of dark black stools indicate internal bleeding.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A person who drinks alcohol regularly is strongly advised to reduce their intake to prevent PUD aggravation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol-containing beverages can cause alcohol flush reactions, exacerbations of rhinitis, and, more seriously and commonly, bronchoconstriction in patients with a history of asthma, and in some cases, urticarial skin eruptions, and systemic dermatitis.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption can cause hypoglycemia in diabetics on certain medications, such as insulin or sulfonylurea, by blocking gluconeogenesis.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol increases insulin response to glucose promoting fat storage and hindering carbohydrate and fat oxidation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] This excess processing in the liver acetyl CoA can lead to fatty liver disease and eventually alcoholic liver disease.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] This progression can lead to further complications, alcohol-related liver disease may cause exocrine pancreatic insufficiency, the inability to properly digest food due to a lack or reduction of digestive enzymes made by the pancreas.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has a variety of short-term and long-term adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol has both short-term, and long-term effects on the memory, and sleep.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It also has reinforcement-related adverse effects, including alcoholism, dependence, and withdrawal.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is directly related to considerable morbidity and mortality, for instance due to intoxication and alcohol-related health problems.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The World Health Organization advises that there is no safe level of alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Many of the toxic and unpleasant actions of alcohol in the body are mediated by its carcinogenic byproduct acetaldehyde.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The amount of ethanol in the body is typically quantified by blood alcohol content (BAC); weight of ethanol per unit volume of blood.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Small doses of ethanol, in general, are stimulant-like and produce euphoria and relaxation; people experiencing these symptoms tend to become talkative and less inhibited, and may exhibit poor judgement.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] At higher dosages (BAC > 1 gram/liter), ethanol acts as a central nervous system (CNS) depressant, producing at progressively higher dosages, impaired sensory and motor function, slowed cognition, stupefaction, unconsciousness, and possible death.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A hangover is the experience of various unpleasant physiological and psychological effects usually following the consumption of alcohol, such as wine, beer, and liquor.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Hangovers can last for several hours or for more than 24 hours.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The long-term effects of alcohol have been extensively researched.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The health effects of long-term alcohol consumption vary depending on the amount consumed.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Even light drinking poses health risks, but atypically small amounts of alcohol may have health benefits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism causes severe health consequences which outweigh any potential benefits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Long-term alcohol consumption is capable of damaging nearly every organ and system in the body.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In addition, damage to the central nervous system and peripheral nervous system (e.g., painful peripheral neuropathy) can occur from chronic heavy alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] There is also an increased risk for accidental injuries, for example, those sustained in traffic accidents and falls.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Excessive alcohol consumption can have a negative impact on aging.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Conversely, light intake of alcohol may have some beneficial effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The association of alcohol intake with reduced cardiovascular risk has been noted since 1904 and remains even after adjusting for known confounders.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Light alcohol intake is also associated with reduced risk of type 2 diabetes, gastritis, and cholelithiasis.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, these are only observational studies and high-quality evidence for the beneficial effects of alcohol is nonexistent.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol causes a plethora of detrimental effects in society.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in delphic analysis regarding 20 popular recreational substances.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was ranked 6th in dependence, 11th in physical harm, and 2nd in social harm.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol use is stereotypically associated with crime, more so than other drugs like marijuana.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Many emergency room visits involve alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] As many as 15% of employees show problematic alcohol-related behaviors in the workplace, such as drinking before going to work or even drinking on the job.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drunk dialing refers to an intoxicated person making phone calls that they would not likely make if sober.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol availability and consumption rates and alcohol rates are positively associated with nuisance, loitering, panhandling, and disorderly conduct in open spaces.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking, or heavy episodic drinking, is drinking alcoholic beverages with an intention of becoming intoxicated by heavy consumption of alcohol over a short period of time.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Binge drinking is associated with risks such as suicide, sexual assault, cardiovascular issues, and brain damage, more acutely than alcohol use in general.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcoholism or its medical diagnosis *alcohol use disorder* refers to alcohol addiction, alcohol dependence, dipsomania, and/or alcohol abuse.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It is a major problem and many health problems as well as death can result from excessive alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is linked to a lifespan that is reduced by about 12 years relative to the average person.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In 2004, it was estimated that 4% of deaths worldwide were attributable to alcohol use.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Deaths from alcohol are split about evenly between acute causes (e.g., overdose, accidents) and chronic conditions.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The leading chronic alcohol-related condition associated with death is alcoholic liver disease.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol dependence is also associated with cognitive impairment and organic brain damage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Some researchers have found that even one alcoholic drink a day increases an individual's risk of health problems by 0.4%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Two or more consecutive alcohol-free days a week have been recommended to improve health and break dependence.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Discontinuation of alcohol after extended heavy use and associated tolerance development (resulting in dependence) can result in alcohol withdrawal.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the most dangerous drugs to withdraw from.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol withdrawal can cause confusion, paranoia, anxiety, insomnia, agitation, tremors, fever, nausea, vomiting, autonomic dysfunction, seizures, and hallucinations.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Delirium tremens is a condition that develops in some cases of severe withdrawal, with onset typically 48–72 hours after discontinuation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It is considered a medical emergency and should be treated in an inpatient or intensive care unit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Symptoms of ethanol overdose may include nausea, vomiting, CNS depression, coma, acute respiratory failure, or death.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Levels of even less than 0.1% can cause intoxication, with unconsciousness often occurring at 0.3–0.4%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Death from ethanol consumption is possible when blood alcohol levels reach 0.4%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A blood level of 0.5% or more is commonly fatal.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The oral median lethal dose (LD50) of ethanol in rats is 5,628 mg/kg.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Directly translated to human beings, this would mean that if a person who weighs 70 kg (150 lb) drank a 500 mL (17 US fl oz) glass of pure ethanol, they would have an estimated 50% risk of dying.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The highest blood alcohol level ever recorded, in which the subject survived, is 1.41%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol-induced dose dumping (AIDD) is an unintended rapid release of large amounts of a given drug, when administered through a modified-release dosage while co-ingesting ethanol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] This is considered a pharmaceutical disadvantage due to the high risk of causing drug-induced toxicity by increasing the absorption and serum concentration above the therapeutic window of the drug.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The best way to prevent this interaction is by avoiding the co-ingestion of both substances or using specific controlled-release formulations that are resistant to AIDD.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Particular drugs of concern are antipsychotics and certain antidepressants.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol can intensify the sedation caused by hypnotics and sedatives such as barbiturates, benzodiazepines, sedative antihistamines, opioids, nonbenzodiazepines/Z-drugs (such as zolpidem and zopiclone).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Disulfiram inhibits the enzyme acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, which in turn results in buildup of acetaldehyde, a toxic metabolite of ethanol with unpleasant effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The medication or drug is commonly used to treat alcohol use disorder, and results in immediate hangover-like symptoms upon consumption of alcohol, this effect is widely known as disulfiram effect.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is an antibacterial agent that kills bacteria by damaging cellular DNA and hence cellular function.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Metronidazole is usually given to people who have diarrhea caused by *Clostridioides difficile* bacteria.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Patients who are taking metronidazole are sometimes advised to avoid alcohol, even after 1 hour following the last dose.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Although older data suggested a possible disulfiram-like effect of metronidazole, newer data has challenged this and suggests it does not actually have this effect.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and alcohol both increase gastrointestinal events such as gastrointestinal bleeding and peptic ulcers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Taking the two together further increases the risk additively.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The risk of stomach bleeding is still increased when aspirin is taken with alcohol or warfarin.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol enhances the bioavailability of methylphenidate (elevated plasma dexmethylphenidate).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethylphenidate formation appears to be more common when large quantities of methylphenidate and alcohol are consumed at the same time, such as in non-medical use or overdose scenarios.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, only a small percent of the consumed methylphenidate is converted to ethylphenidate.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] While nicotinis mimic the name of classic cocktails like the appletini (their name deriving from "martini"), combining nicotine with alcohol may cause adverse effects.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Tobacco and nicotine actually heighten cravings for alcohol, making this a risky mix.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Controlled animal and human studies showed that caffeine (energy drinks) in combination with alcohol increased the craving for more alcohol more strongly than alcohol alone.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] These findings correspond to epidemiological data that people who consume energy drinks generally showed an increased tendency to take alcohol and other substances.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol interacts with cocaine *in vivo* to produce cocaethylene, another psychoactive substance which may be substantially more cardiotoxic than either cocaine or alcohol by themselves.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In combination with cannabis, ethanol increases plasma tetrahydrocannabinol levels, which suggests that ethanol may increase the absorption of tetrahydrocannabinol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Excessive use of alcohol is known to affect the metabolism of warfarin and can elevate the INR, and thus increase the risk of bleeding.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) product insert on warfarin states that alcohol should be avoided.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Cleveland Clinic suggests that when taking warfarin one should not drink more than "one beer, 6 oz of wine, or one shot of alcohol per day".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Use of isoniazid should be carefully monitored in daily alcohol drinkers since they may be more likely to develop isoniazid-associated hepatitis.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol works in the brain primarily by increasing the effects of GABA (γ-aminobutyric acid), the major inhibitory neurotransmitter in the brain; by facilitating GABA's actions in the GABAA receptor, alcohol suppresses the activity of the central nervous system.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol also directly affects a number of other neurotransmitter systems including those of glutamate, glycine, acetylcholine, and serotonin.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The pleasurable effects of alcohol ingestion are the result of increased levels of dopamine and endogenous opioids in the reward pathways of the brain.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] After oral ingestion, ethanol is absorbed via the stomach and intestines into the bloodstream.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is highly water-soluble and diffuses passively throughout the entire body, including the brain.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Soon after ingestion, it begins to be metabolized, 90% or more by the liver.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] One standard drink is sufficient to almost completely saturate the liver's capacity to metabolize alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The main metabolite is acetaldehyde, a toxic carcinogen.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Acetaldehyde is then further metabolized into ionic acetate by the enzyme aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Acetate is not carcinogenic and has low toxicity, but has been implicated in causing hangovers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Acetate is further broken down into carbon dioxide and water and eventually eliminated from the body through urine and breath.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] 5 to 10% of ethanol is excreted unchanged in the breath, urine, and sweat.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is also known chemically as alcohol, ethyl alcohol, or drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It is a simple alcohol with a molecular formula of C2H6O and a molecular weight of 46.0684 g/mol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The molecular formula of ethanol may also be written as CH3−CH2−OH or as C2H5−OH.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The latter can also be thought of as an ethyl group linked to a hydroxyl (alcohol) group and can be abbreviated as EtOH.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is a volatile, flammable, colorless liquid with a slight characteristic odor.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Aside from its use as a psychoactive and recreational substance, ethanol is also commonly used as an antiseptic and disinfectant, a chemical and medicinal solvent, and a fuel.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is only one of several types of chemical alcohols, and has a variety of analogues.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Most other alcohols are considered poisonous.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In general, higher alcohols are less toxic.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages are sometimes laced with toxic alcohols.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The toxicity of isopropyl alcohol is about twice that of ethanol; a mild, brief exposure to isopropyl alcohol is unlikely to cause any serious harm, although ingesting significant quantities can lead to vomiting, abdominal pain, and internal bleeding.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ingestion of as little as 3.16 grams of methanol can cause irreversible optic nerve damage, and the oral LD50 for humans is estimated to be 56.2 grams.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Many methanol poisoning incidents have occurred through history. n-Butanol is reported to produce similar effects to those of ethanol and relatively low toxicity (one-sixth of that of ethanol in one rat study).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] However, its vapors can produce eye irritation, and inhalation can cause pulmonary edema.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Acetone (propanone) is a ketone rather than an alcohol, and is reported to produce similar toxic effects; it can be extremely damaging to the cornea.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Although ethanol is the most prevalent alcohol in alcoholic beverages, alcoholic beverages contain several types of psychoactive alcohols, that are categorized as primary, secondary, or tertiary.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Primary and secondary alcohols, are oxidized to aldehydes, and ketones, respectively, while tertiary alcohols are generally resistant to oxidation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Lucas test differentiates between primary, secondary, and tertiary alcohols.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The tertiary alcohol *tert*-amyl alcohol (TAA), also known as 2-methylbutan-2-ol (2M2B), has a history of use as a hypnotic and anesthetic, as do other tertiary alcohols such as methylpentynol, ethchlorvynol, and chloralodol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Unlike primary alcohols like ethanol, these tertiary alcohols cannot be oxidized into aldehyde or carboxylic acid metabolites, which are often toxic, and for this reason, these compounds are safer in comparison.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Other relatives of ethanol with similar effects include chloral hydrate, paraldehyde, and many volatile and inhalational anesthetics (e.g., chloroform, diethyl ether, and isoflurane).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol is produced naturally as a byproduct of the metabolic processes of yeast and hence is present in any yeast habitat, including even endogenously in humans, but it does not cause raised blood alcohol content as seen in the rare medical condition auto-brewery syndrome (ABS).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It is manufactured through hydration of ethylene or by brewing via fermentation of sugars with yeast (most commonly *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The sugars are commonly obtained from sources like steeped cereal grains (e.g., barley), grape juice, and sugarcane products (e.g., molasses, sugarcane juice).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Ethanol–water mixture which can be further purified via distillation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol is one of the oldest recreational drugs.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The word "Alcohol" originates from the Arabic word *al-kuhul,* which refers to a fine metallic powder that was used to paint the eyelids darker.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcoholic beverages have been produced since the Neolithic period, as early as 7000 BC in China.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol was brewed as early as 7,000 to 6,650 BCE in northern China.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Gin Craze was a period in the first half of the 18th century when the consumption of gin increased rapidly in Great Britain, especially in London.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] By 1743, The average English person was drinking 2.2 gallons (10 litres) of gin per year.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Sale of Spirits Act 1750 (commonly known as the Gin Act 1751) was an Act of the Parliament of Great Britain (24 Geo.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] 40) which was enacted to reduce the consumption of gin and other distilled spirits, a popular pastime that was regarded as one of the primary causes of crime in London.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The rum ration (also called the tot) was a daily amount of rum given to sailors on Royal Navy ships.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] It started 1866 and was abolished in 1970 after concerns that the intake of strong alcohol would lead to unsteady hands when working machinery.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Andrew Johnson alcoholism debate is the dispute, originally conducted among the general public, and now typically a question for historians, about whether or not Andrew Johnson, the 17th president of the United States (1865–1869), drank to excess.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The prohibition in the United States era was the period from 1920 to 1933 when the United States prohibited the production, importation, transportation, and sale of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The nationwide ban on alcoholic beverages, was repealed by the passage of the Twenty-first Amendment to the United States Constitution on December 5, 1933.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Bratt System was a system that was used in Sweden (1919–1955) and similarly in Finland (1944–1970) to control alcohol consumption, by rationing of liquor.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Every citizen allowed to consume alcohol was given a booklet called a motbok (viinakortti in Finland), in which a stamp was added each time a purchase was made at Systembolaget (in Sweden) and Alko (in Finland).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A similar system also existed in Estonia between July 1, 1920, to December 31, 1925.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The stamps were based on the amount of alcohol bought.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] When a certain amount of alcohol had been bought, the owner of the booklet had to wait until next month to buy more.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The Medicinal Liquor Prescriptions Act of 1933 was a law passed by Congress in response to the abuse of medicinal liquor prescriptions during Prohibition.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Gilbert Paul Jordan (aka The Boozing Barber) was a Canadian serial killer who is believed to have committed the so-called "alcohol murders" between 1965–c.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The consumption of alcohol is deeply embedded in social practices and rituals, often celebrated as a cornerstone of community gatherings and personal milestones.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drinking culture is the set of traditions and social behaviours that surround the consumption of alcoholic beverages as a recreational drug and social lubricant.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Alcohol consumption is fully legal and available in most countries of the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Home made alcoholic beverages with low alcohol content like wine, and beer is also legal in most countries, but distilling moonshine outside of a registered distillery remains illegal in most of them.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Some majority-Muslim countries, such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Pakistan, Iran, and Libya prohibit the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages because they are forbidden by Islam.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Also, laws banning alcohol consumption are found in some Indian states as well as some Native American reservations in the U.S.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In addition, there are regulations on alcohol sales and use in many countries throughout the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] For instance, the majority of countries have a minimum legal drinking age to purchase or consume alcoholic beverages, although there are often exceptions such as underage consumption of small amounts of alcohol with parental supervision.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Also, some countries have bans on public intoxication.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Drinking while driving or intoxicated driving is frequently outlawed, and it may be illegal to have an open container of alcohol or liquor bottle in an automobile, bus, or aircraft.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The legality of sex under alcohol influence varies by country and the threshold of "too drunk" for sexual consent can be ambiguous.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Religion and alcohol have a complex history.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The world's religions have had different relationships with alcohol, reflecting diverse cultural, social, and religious practices across different traditions.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] While some religions strictly prohibit alcohol consumption, viewing it as sinful or harmful to spiritual and physical well-being, others incorporate it into their rituals and ceremonies.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Throughout history, alcohol has held significant roles in religious observances, from the use of sacramental wine in Christian sacraments to the offering and moderate drinking of omiki (sacramental sake) in Shinto purification rituals.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A study in 2015 found that alcohol and tobacco use combined resulted in a significant health burden, costing over a quarter of a billion disability-adjusted life years.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Illicit drug use caused tens of millions more disability-adjusted life years.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] According to *The Lancet*, 'four industries (tobacco, unhealthy food, fossil fuel, and alcohol) are responsible for at least a third of global deaths per year'.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] In 2024, the World Health Organization published a report including these figures.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Many Native Americans in the United States have been harmed by, or become addicted to, drinking alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] Qualitative analysis reveals that the alcohol industry likely misinforms the public about the dangers of alcohol, similar to the tobacco industry.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The alcohol industry influences alcohol policy and health messages, including those for schoolchildren.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The alcohol consumption recommendations (or *safe limits*) varies from no intake, to daily, weekly, or daily/weekly guidelines provided by health agencies of governments.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] A standard drink is a measure of alcohol consumption representing a fixed amount of pure ethanol, used in relation to recommendations about alcohol consumption and its relative risks to health.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-drug] The size of a standard drink varies from 8g to 20g across countries, but 10g alcohol (12.7 millilitres) is used in the World Health Organization (WHO) Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT)'s questionnaire form example, and has been adopted by more countries than any other amount.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The measurement of alcohol content and the statement of content on bottles of alcoholic beverages is regulated by law in many countries.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] In 1972, Canada phased out the use of "proof"; in 1973, the European Union followed suit; and the United Kingdom, where the concept originated, started using ABV instead in 1980.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The United States Code mandates the use of ABV, but permits proof to be used also.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The degree symbol (°) is sometimes used to indicate alcohol proof, either alone (e.g.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] 10°) or after a space and joined to the letter P as a unit name (e.g.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The term *proof* dates back to 16th century England, when spirits were taxed at different rates depending on their alcohol content.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Similar terminology and methodology spread to other nations as spirit distillation, and taxation, became common.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] In England, spirits were originally tested with a basic "burn-or-no-burn" test, in which an alcohol-containing liquid that would ignite was said to be "above proof", and one which would not was said to be "under proof".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] A liquid just alcoholic enough to maintain combustion was defined as 100 proof and was the basis for taxation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Because the flash point of alcohol is highly dependent on temperature, 100 proof defined this way ranges from 20% at 36 °C (97 °F) to 96% at 13 °C (55 °F) alcohol by *weight* (ABW); at 24 °C (75 °F) 100 proof would be 50% AB*W*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Another early method for testing liquor's alcohol content was the "gunpowder method".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Gunpowder was soaked in a spirit, and if the gunpowder could still burn, the spirit was rated above proof.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] This test relies on the fact that potassium nitrate (a chemical in gunpowder) is significantly more soluble in water than in alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] While less influenced by temperature than the simpler burn-or-no-burn test, gunpowder tests also lacked true reproducibility.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Factors including the grain size of gunpowder and the time it sat in the spirit impact the dissolution of potassium nitrate and therefore what would be defined as 100 proof.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] However, the gunpowder method is significantly less variable than the burn-or-no-burn method, and 100 proof defined by it is traditionally defined as 57.15% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] By the end of the 17th century, England had introduced tests based on specific gravity for defining proof.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] However, it was not until 1816 that a legal standard based on specific density was defined in England.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] 100 proof was defined as a spirit with 12⁄13 the specific gravity of pure water at the same temperature.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] From the 19th century until 1 January 1980, the UK officially measured alcohol content by proof spirit, defined as spirit with a gravity of 12⁄13 that of water, or 923 kg/m3 (1,556 lb/cu yd), and equivalent to 57.15% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] This led to the approximation that 100-proof spirit has an ABV of 4⁄7.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] From this, it follows that to convert the ABV expressed as a percentage to degrees proof, it is only necessary to multiply the ABV by 7⁄4.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Thus pure 100% alcohol will have 100×(7⁄4) = 175 proof, and a spirit containing 40% ABV will have 40×(7⁄4) = 70 proof.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The proof system in the United States was established around 1848 and was based on percent alcohol rather than specific gravity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Fifty percent alcohol by volume was defined as 100 proof.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] This is different from 50% volume fraction (expressed as a percentage); the latter does not take into account change in volume on mixing, whereas the former does.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] To make 50% ABV from pure alcohol, one would take 50 parts of alcohol and dilute to 100 parts of solution with water, all the while mixing the solution.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] To make 50% alcohol by volume fraction, one would take 50 parts alcohol and 50 parts water, measured separately, and then mix them together.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The resulting volume will not be 100 parts but between 96 and 97 parts, since the smaller water molecules can take up some of the space between the larger alcohol molecules (see volume change).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The use of proof as a measure of alcohol content is now mostly linguistic and historical.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Today, liquor is sold in most locations with labels that state its percentage alcohol by volume.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The European Union (EU) follows recommendations of the International Organization of Legal Metrology (OIML).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] 22 (1973) provides standards for measuring alcohol strength by volume and by mass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] A preference for one method over the other is not stated in the document, but if alcohol strength by volume is used, it must be expressed as a percentage of total volume at a temperature of 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The document does not address alcohol proof or the labeling of bottles.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] On 1 January 1980, Britain adopted the ABV system of measurement prescribed by the European Union, of which it was then a member.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The OIML recommendation for ABV used by the EU states the alcohol by volume in a mixture containing alcohol as a percentage of the total volume of the mixture at a temperature of 293.15 K [20.00 °C; 68.00 °F].
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] It replaced the Sikes hydrometer method of measuring the proof of spirits, which had been used in Britain for over 160 years.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] In the United States, alcohol content is legally mandated to be specified as an ABV percentage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] For bottled spirits over 100 ml (3.5 imp fl oz; 3.4 US fl oz) containing no solids, actual alcohol content is allowed to vary by up to 0.15% of the ABV stated on the label.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] By contrast, bottled spirits which are less than 100 ml (as well as those which otherwise contain solids) may vary by up to 0.25%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Proof (the term *degrees proof* is not used), defined as being twice the percentage of alcohol by volume, may be optionally stated in conjunction with the ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] For example, whisky may be labeled as 50% ABV and as 100 proof; 86-proof whisky contains 43% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The most typical bottling proof for spirits in the United States is 80 US proof, and there is special legal recognition of 100-proof spirits in the bottled in bond category defined since 1897.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The Code of Federal Regulations requires that liquor labels state the percentage of ABV at a temperature of 60 °F (16 °C).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] The regulation permits, but does not require, a statement of the proof, provided that it is printed close to the ABV number.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] In practice, proof levels continue to be stated on nearly all spirits labels in the United States, and are more commonly used than ABV when describing spirits in journalism and informal settings.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcohol-proof] Beverages were labelled by alcohol proof in Canada until 1972, then replaced by ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcoholic-beverage] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] The term *alcopop* (a portmanteau of the words *alcohol* and *pop*) is used commonly in the United Kingdom and Ireland to describe these drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In English-speaking Canada, "cooler" is more common but "alcopop" may also be used.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Other terms include flavored alcoholic beverage (**FAB**), flavored malt beverage (**FMB**), "pre-packaged" or "premium packaged" spirit (**PPS**).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In Australia and New Zealand "premix" and ready to drink (**RTD**) are both commonly used terms.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] "Spirit cooler" is used in South Africa for distilled alcohol versions.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Hard seltzer is a related category of alcoholic drinks based on flavored seltzer water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Hard soda, meanwhile, is specifically related to soft drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Hard lemonade, which could be considered an alcopop, has been around for some time.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Hard cider, on the other hand, is a fermented beverage similar to wine or beer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] There are a variety of beverages produced and marketed around the world as well as within each market which are described as coolers or alcopops.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] They tend to be sweet and served in small bottles (typically 355 ml (the normal size of a soda pop can) in the US, 275 ml in South Africa and Germany, 330 ml in Canada and Europe), and between 4% and 7% ABV.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In Europe, Canada, and South Africa coolers tend to be pre-mixed spirits, including vodka (e.g.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In the United States, on the other hand, alcopops often start out as un-hopped beers, depending on the state in which they are sold.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Much of the malt (and alcohol) is removed (leaving mostly water), with subsequent addition of alcohol (usually vodka or grain alcohol), sugar, coloring and flavoring.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Such drinks are legally classified as beers in virtually all states and can therefore be sold in outlets that do not or cannot carry spirit-based drinks.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] There are, however, stronger ones that *are* simply pre-mixed spirits (e.g.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Bacardi Rum Island Iced Tea), often containing about 12.5% alcohol by volume, that can be sold only where hard liquor is available.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Wine coolers gained popularity in the US market in the 1980s when Bartles and Jaymes began advertising their brand of wine coolers, which were followed by other brands, including when Bacardi introduced the Breezer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Later, Mike's Hard Lemonade was released in the United States, with humorous commercials depicting what they called "violence against lemons".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Smirnoff also came out with another citrus-flavored malt beverage in the United States in the late 1990s called Smirnoff Ice, which promoted itself with flashy commercials, usually involving trendy young people dancing in unlikely situations and places.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Through its Alcopop-Free Zone® campaign, " Alcohol Justice has sought to ban alcopop sales entirely since the sweet and brightly colored alcoholic drinks may appeal to children.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Many cooler advertising campaigns have been criticized as trying to make alcopops appeal to young drinkers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In the United Kingdom, a media outcry during the mid-1990s arose as the tabloid press associated alcopops with under-age drinking which damaged sales and led to British liquor stores withdrawing them from their shelves.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In response to a complaint from the Center for Science in the Public Interest (CSPI), the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) conducted an extensive investigation in 2001.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] The agency "found no evidence of intent to target minors with FMB products, packaging, or advertising.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] The Federal Trade Commission again in 2003 investigated FMB ads, product placement, and internal company marketing documents after a directive from the conferees of the House and Senate Appropriations Committees.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] "The Commission's investigation found no evidence of targeting underage consumers in the marketing of FMBs.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In December 2003, Ireland raised the tax on flavored malt beverages to equal that of spirits, the second-highest in Europe.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Germany has imposed an extra duty of 0.80 to 0.90 euro per bottle effective August 1, 2004.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] To circumvent higher taxation, some German producers have switched to wine coolers, which are being marketed the same way.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Some bottles now carry a warning stating that they are not for consumption by people under the legal drinking age (under 18 in the UK and 21 in the United States).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] On May 11, 2008, the Australian Government increased the excise tax on alcopops by 70%, to bring it in line with the tax on spirits.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] There is the concern this tax will encourage consumers to buy straight spirits and mix the drinks themselves, possibly resulting in drinks with a higher alcohol concentration than the premixed alternatives.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] This tax was revoked during March 2009 meaning the government had to pay back the 290 million collected on the tax.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] The Federal Trade Commission report states, "Further, industry-conducted research on consumers over the age of 21 who use FMBs shows that these consumers generally view the FMBs as substitutes for beer, ...
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] This research also concludes that consumers are not likely to consume more than two or three FMBs on any occasion because of the products' sweetness.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In March 2018, Coca-Cola announced it would be launching an alcopop product for the first time, a *chūhai* beverage in Japan.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Brands of coolers are numerous and their alcoholic base vary greatly.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Some notable brands include: VK, Smirnoff Ice, Mike's Hard Lemonade, Bacardi Breezer, Palm Bay, Skyy Blue, Jack Daniel's mixed with Coca-Cola and, in the UK, WKD Original Vodka.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Garage is an alcopop produced by the Finnish brewery Sinebrychoff.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Alcohol-based sugar-sweetened beverages like alcopop are closely linked to episodic drinking in adolescents.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] The Australian government increased the tax on these drinks under the 2008 budget to the same rate as spirits, volumetrically, in an effort to stop binge drinking.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] The tax was criticized by the opposition as a tax grab, and voted down in the Senate on March 18, 2009.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Before its rejection, the tax had already raised at least A$290 million after April 2008.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In April 2009, some Labor party MPs planned to resubmit the tax to the Senate, and it was finally approved in August 2009, increasing the tax on the drinks from $39.36 to $66.67 per litre of alcohol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] A 2013 study concluded that the tax had no impact on binge drinking of the drinks by teenagers.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] On 1 July 2004 the German government increased the tax on mixed drinks based on spirits (e.g. vodka, rum) by roughly one Euro per 275-ml-bottle in order to discourage teenagers drinking excessively, although those drinks were already prohibited for those under the age of 18.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In 2019, some senators including Pia Cayetano and former Special Assistant to the President Bong Go called for pullout of alcopops from the market due to "deceptive packaging that resembles fruit juices usually bought by young consumers".
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Alcopops also have seven percent alcohol content, which is slightly lower than that of local beer brand Red Horse Beer.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] Systembolaget blocked the sale of alcoholic soft drinks in Sweden until mid-1996, when Alkoholsortimentsnämnden decided, with reference to Treaty of Rome Article 30, that Systembolaget could not refuse to sell certain products.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] This led to great debate, where the marketing of the alcoholic soft drink was considered to be aimed above all at young people.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] After initially great sales successes, the popularity has now declined, and many of the alcoholic drinks' market shares have been taken over by sweeter varieties of cider that share many characteristics with the soft drink but have been fermented to their alcoholic strength.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/alcopop] In June 1997, Co-op Food became the first major retailer to place an outright ban on the sale of alcopops in its shops.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] In thermodynamics, an **apparent molar property** of a solution component in a mixture or solution is a quantity defined with the purpose of isolating the contribution of each component to the non-ideality of the mixture.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] It shows the change in the corresponding solution property (for example, volume) per mole of that component added, when all of that component is added to the solution.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] It is described as *apparent* because it appears to represent the molar property of that component *in solution*, provided that the properties of the other solution components are assumed to remain constant during the addition.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] However this assumption is often not justified, since the values of apparent molar properties of a component may be quite different from its molar properties in the pure state.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] By dividing this relation to the molar amount of one component a relation between the apparent molar property of a component and the mixing ratio of components can be obtained.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] However this assumption must often be considered unrealistic as shown in the examples below, so that ⁠ ${}^{\phi }{\tilde {V}}_{1}\,$ ⁠ is described only as an *apparent* value.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] An apparent molar quantity can be similarly defined for the component identified as solvent ⁠ ${}^{\phi }{\tilde {V}}_{0}\,$ ⁠.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Some authors have reported apparent molar volumes of both (liquid) components of the same solution.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] This procedure can be extended to ternary and multicomponent mixtures.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Apparent quantities can also be expressed using mass instead of number of moles.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] This expression produces apparent specific quantities, like the apparent specific volume.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] where the specific quantities are denoted with small letters.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Apparent (molar) properties are not constants (even at a given temperature), but are functions of the composition.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] At infinite dilution, an apparent molar property and the corresponding partial molar property become equal.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Some apparent molar properties that are commonly used are apparent molar enthalpy, apparent molar heat capacity, and apparent molar volume.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] The apparent (molal) volume of a solute can be expressed as a function of the molality *b* of that solute (and of the densities of the solution and solvent).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] The sum of products molalities – apparent molar volumes of solutes in their binary solutions equals the product between the sum of molalities of solutes and apparent molar volume in ternary of multicomponent solution mentioned above.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] to the number of moles of one component.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] In other words, we assume that the volume of the solvent does not change, and we use the partial molar volume where the number of moles of the solute is exactly zero ("the molar volume").
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] the term $V_{0}$ is attributed to the pure solvent, while the "leftover" excess volume, ${}^{\phi }V_{1}$ , is considered to originate from the solute.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] At high dilution with $n_{0}\gg n_{1}\approx 0$ , we have ${\tilde {V_{0}}}\approx {\bar {V_{0}}}$ , and so the apparent molar volume and partial molar volume of the solute also converge: ${}^{\phi }{\tilde {V}}_{1}\approx {\bar {V}}_{1}$ .
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Quantitatively, the relation between partial molar properties and the apparent ones can be derived from the definition of the apparent quantities and of the molality.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] where ν is the number of ions due to dissociation of the electrolyte, and b is the molality as above.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] The apparent molar volume of salt is usually less than the molar volume of the solid salt.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] For instance, solid NaCl has a volume of 27 cm3 per mole, but the apparent molar volume at low concentrations is only 16.6 cc/mole.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] In fact, some aqueous electrolytes have negative apparent molar volumes: NaOH −6.7, LiOH −6.0, and Na2CO3 −6.7 cm3/mole.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] This means that their solutions in a given amount of water have a smaller volume than the same amount of pure water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] (The effect is small, however.) The physical reason is that nearby water molecules are strongly attracted to the ions so that they occupy less space.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Another example of the apparent molar volume of the second component is less than its molar volume as a pure substance is the case of ethanol in water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] For example, at 20 mass percents ethanol, the solution has a volume of 1.0326 liters per kg at 20 °C, while pure water is 1.0018 L/kg (1.0018 cc/g).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] However pure ethanol has a molar volume at this temperature of 58.4 cc/mole (1.27 cc/g).
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] If the solution were ideal, its volume would be the sum of the unmixed components.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] The nonideality of the solution is reflected by a slight decrease (roughly 2.2%, 1.0326 rather than 1.055 L/kg) in the volume of the combined system upon mixing.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] As the percent ethanol goes up toward 100%, the apparent molar volume rises to the molar volume of pure ethanol.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Apparent quantities can underline interactions in electrolyte – non-electrolyte systems which show interactions like salting in and salting out, but also give insights in ion-ion interactions, especially by their dependence on temperature.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] For multicomponent solutions, apparent molar properties can be defined in several ways.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] For the volume of a *ternary* (3-component) solution with one solvent and two solutes as an example, there would still be only one equation $(V={\tilde {V}}_{0}n_{0}+{}^{\phi }{\tilde {V}}_{1}n_{1}+{}^{\phi }{\tilde {V}}_{2}n_{2})$ , which is insufficient to determine the two apparent volumes.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] (This is in contrast to partial molar properties, which are well-defined intensive properties of the materials and therefore unambiguously defined in multicomponent systems.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] where V is the solution volume and $V_{0}$ the volume of pure water.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] This method can be extended for mixtures with more than 3 components.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] Another method is to treat the ternary system as *pseudobinary* and define the apparent molar volume of each solute with reference to a binary system containing both other components: water and the other solute.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] However, this is an unsatisfactory description of volumetric properties.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] There are situations when there is no rigorous way to define which is solvent and which is solute like in the case of liquid mixtures (say water and ethanol) that can dissolve or not a solid like sugar or salt.
[src:alcohol-by-volume/apparent-molar-property] In these cases apparent molar properties can and must be ascribed to all components of the mixture.
